ish- and Chinese-speaking worlds explore Zhu Xi's unique thought and offer it to the Western philosophical imagination. Zhu Xi's vision is critical, intellectually rigorous, and religious, telling us how to live in the transforming world of li—the emergent, immanent, and coherent patternings of natural and human milieu.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aZhu, Xi, 1130-1200. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Eastern.2bisacsh1 aAdler, Joseph A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmes, Roger T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAngle, Stephen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaba, Eiho, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerthrong, John H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Kuan-Hung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColwell, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoyle, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuoxiang, Peng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanson, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHe, Jinli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHe, Jinli, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHuang, Yahui Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKim, Yung Sik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato